The following segments introduce the PISCES model, detailing its structure and objectives. PISCES stands for "Pre-Trained Many-to-Many Model." It involves meta-pretraining where the model processes multi-lingual unlabeled corpora, followed by cross-lingual parallel pretraining incorporating bilingual parallel corpora, and finally task-specific pretraining utilizing monolingual corpora. The design ensures thorough preparation of the model before applying it to real-world tasks. The explanation underscores the advantages of such a unified architecture over conventional approaches, enabling efficient handling of numerous languages and improving the accuracy and comprehensiveness of translations and summaries produced by the system.

This is a slide from Avignon Université. It features the title "Language Modeling" in bold red text at the top, followed by detailed information about pre-training strategies and data sources for NLP tasks.
The main points include:
- DRBERT achieves state-of-the-art results on 9 downstream French medical-oriented tasks. - Surpasses Camembert generic model and English-based domain-specific models. - Confirms utility of training a medical-specific model in French. - Data sources matter; training on heterogeneous data leads to better performance than using private clinical data only. - Continual pretraining works effectively when based on domain-specific English models. - The DRBERT models are freely available under the MIT license with source code hosted on GitHub.
The bottom section provides more details: - Evaluation: Performance evaluation of 13 models across various datasets (NER, CNER, POS, CAS). - Data sources matters; training on heterogeneous data yields superior results compared to exclusive use of private clinical data. - Continual pretraining proves effective with domain-specific English models. - DRBERT's models offer robustness against private clinical data challenges due to continual pretraining. - The models' scripts can be found on GitHub, specifically under the repository "drbert."
The presentation concludes with contact information for further inquiries or collaboration opportunities regarding these findings.
Overall, it emphasizes the importance of utilizing diverse data sources and continuous learning methods to enhance language modeling capabilities, particularly within specific domains like healthcare.
The slide also includes logos for Avignon Université and PubMed, indicating institutional affiliations related to the research presented.
The final part encourages networking during an upcoming poster session in Toronto, providing additional resources via URLs for those interested in exploring the work further.

The slide titled "Conclusion" provides a summary of the main points discussed in the presentation. It highlights three key ingredients needed for good generalization: better model architecture, larger model size, and more fine-tuning examples. The performance drop is attributed to temporal drift rather than adaptive overfitting.
The conclusion also includes an experimental setup where CoNLL-2003 taggers were retrained with modern data from 2023 using CoNLL-2019 guidelines. The results show that these taggers still work well even after being trained on updated datasets. However, there are some challenges related to temporal drift, which can be observed by comparing the F1 scores across different years (2004 and beyond).
Additionally, the presenter shares their contact information via email (sliu775@gatech.edu) for further inquiries or collaborations regarding the research findings presented.

The presentation slide titled "Language Modeling" from Avignon Université, dated 2018-06-19. The content focuses on evaluating the performance of different pre-training strategies and data sources for biomedical tasks in French.
The first bullet point highlights that DrBERT achieves state-of-the-art results in nine downstream French medical-oriented tasks. The second bullet emphasizes the importance of training a medical-specific model in French using heterogeneous data. The third bullet discusses the advantages of NACHOS over private clinical data only. The fourth bullet notes that more data is better but does not scale well. The fifth bullet suggests continual pretraining as an effective strategy when based on domain-specific English models. The sixth bullet mentions that all the models are freely available under the MIT license with training scripts accessible via GitHub.
The final section provides contact information: "drbert.univ-avignon.fr."

The content throughout the slides provides detailed information about language learners' capabilities, data annotation processes, and experimental results related to NLP annotations. It includes tables comparing ground truth accuracy versus labels from native speakers and language learners for different tasks such as sentiment analysis, word meaning questions, translation errors, and more. Additionally, there are visual aids like diagrams showing examples of how language learners annotate sentences using dictionaries and translations, emphasizing their learning effect and contributions to building reliable datasets.
The overall theme revolves around questioning the necessity of recruiting native speakers for data annotation and exploring the feasibility of using language learners as annotators instead. This work suggests broadening NLP research for many languages where resources might be limited.
The speaker discusses various aspects of language learner proficiency, mentioning specific tools like the Oxford English Dictionary and the Korean dictionary, which aid them in translating words accurately. They highlight the challenges faced by low-resource languages when trying to recruit native speakers but also emphasize the potential benefits of leveraging language learners who can contribute significantly to improving NLP models through accurate annotations.
The discussion covers topics such as standardization tests, multi-choice question formats, and practical applications involving language learners, demonstrating their ability to provide valuable insights into annotating texts effectively. The study aims to explore ways to overcome barriers associated with collecting high-quality annotated data in less resource-rich linguistic environments.
Throughout the presentation, the use of language learners shows promising outcomes in terms of their performance compared to native speakers, suggesting they could potentially replace traditional methods of data annotation in certain scenarios. The conclusion reiterates the significance of these findings and encourages further exploration into expanding natural language processing (NLP) research across diverse language groups. The slide titled "What Causes Performance Drop?" is part of a presentation discussing the performance drop in named entity recognition models. The presenter, Shuheng Liu from Georgia Tech's School of Interactive Computing and Alan Ritter, presents their findings on why some CoNLL-2003 taggers still work well today despite being developed over 20 years ago.
The main hypothesis presented by the researchers is that adaptive overfitting does not cause significant drops in model accuracy when using more recent data sets like CoNLL++ (CoNLL-2013). They also discuss temporal drift as another factor contributing to performance degradation but conclude that it can be mitigated through fine-tuning with modern datasets or pre-trained language models such as BERT.
The graph shown illustrates how different models perform across various time periods, highlighting trends in F1 scores for both CoNLL-2003 and CoNLL++. It shows improvements in certain models while others show decline due to temporal drifts. Despite these challenges, the study concludes that adapting older models to new contexts remains an effective approach without relying solely on large-scale training data.
The conclusion emphasizes the importance of understanding what causes performance drops in NER tasks and suggests strategies for improving generalization capabilities of existing models based on empirical evidence gathered during their research process.
For further details about this topic, one could refer to the paper available at https://arxiv.org/abs/2212.09747 or contact Shuheng Liu via email at sliu775@gatech.edu. <|speak|>

The slide titled "Neural Divide-and-Conquer Reasoning Framework" is presented, which discusses the integration of neural symbolic calculation and divide-and-conquer reasoning for improving compositional reasoning in large language models. The framework aims to decompose complex reasoning into simple problems and construct a reasoning path.
The slide includes detailed information about the system's performance on various datasets such as CLIP-UNITED, CLIP-WikiText2, and CLIP-ImageNet. It highlights that System 1 (the proposed method) outperforms other baselines like CLIP-UNITED, CLIP-WikiText2, and CLIP-ImageNet.
The text emphasizes that both neural symbolic calculation and divide-and-conquer are effective approaches for solving complex reasoning tasks. Additionally, dual-process theory could be integrated with the divide-and-conquer strategy.
The slide also mentions the source: "Feng, L., Li, Y., Zhang, J., & Liu, C. (2023). Neural Divide-and-Conquer Reasoning Framework for Image Retrieval from Linguistically Complex Texts." The paper was published in ACL 2023.
A diagram illustrates the process flow of the framework, showing how different modules work together to achieve better results compared to previous methods. <|listen|>

Shuheng Liu is a Ph.D. student at Georgia Institute of Technology, specializing in Natural Language Processing (NLP). His research focuses on Named Entity Recognition (NER) and its application to CoNLL-2003 dataset. He has been involved in various NER tasks using different models like BERT, Flair, and ELMo. Shuheng's work explores the performance degradation over time due to temporal drifts and adaptive overfitting issues when reusing old datasets for new applications.
Shuheng Liu's contributions include developing the CoNLL++ dataset, which collects news articles from 2019 to 2023, allowing him to investigate how well-established methods perform with more recent data. The results show that while some older techniques still function reasonably, there are notable drops in accuracy compared to newer approaches, indicating challenges associated with maintaining consistent model effectiveness across extended periods. <|speak|><|listen|>

The slide titled "Core Message" summarizes the key findings of their research. It highlights that DrBERT achieves state-of-the-art results in 12 downstream French medical-related tasks, surpassing Camembert, generic models, and English-based domain-specific models. The slide emphasizes the importance of training a medical-specific model for French data sources. It also notes that NACHOS is more robust than using private clinical data only but does not scale well with heterogeneous data. The slide concludes by stating that continual pretraining is a more effective strategy when based on domain-specific English models.
The presentation includes details about the datasets used (NACHOS and PubMedBERT), the performance metrics (NER, CER, F1, POS, and EM), and mentions that all the scripts are freely available under the MIT license from Avignon University's website: drbert.univ-avignon.fr.
The final part of the presentation features a cartoon character wearing a nurse hat holding an EKG lead, symbolizing healthcare or medical themes related to the content discussed throughout the slides.
The video continues with a person presenting at what appears to be a poster session or academic conference setting, as indicated by the background elements such as bookshelves and formal attire. The speaker provides detailed explanations regarding the evaluation process, mentioning specific datasets like NACHOS and PubMedBERT, which were trained on 4GB of data obtained from the Nantes University Hospital Data Warehouse. They highlight the challenges faced due to limited access to public-private data sets and emphasize the benefits of using NACHOS over other approaches. The presenter underscores the advantages of continual pretraining compared to fine-tuning strategies and discusses how these methods perform better on certain tasks despite the limitations imposed by the dataset size. The overall tone remains informative and professional, aimed at conveying significant insights into biomedical modeling techniques and their application within the context of French medical domains.
The text on the slide reads:
``` Evaluation : Data sources and size
- Evaluation of performance of 13 models on almost all tasks - Core message: - DRBERT achieves state-of-the-art results in 12 downstream French medical-related tasks. - Surpasses Camembert generic model and English-based domain-specific models. - Confirms utility of training a medical-specific model in French. - Data sources matters: training on heterogeneous data leads to higher inter-rater variability for the Camembert-based models trained using continual pretraining. - Continual pretraining is a more effective strategy when based on domain-specific English models. - DRBERT models, the NACHOS dataset, and the training scripts are freely available under the MIT license.
- Thank You - Looking forward to exchange at poster session in Toronto! - More information on: drbert.univ-avignon.fr ```

The slide titled "KITMUS Test Suite" presents a structured approach to evaluating models' ability to integrate knowledge from multiple sources. It highlights the necessity of task-specific training for effective knowledge integration in natural language understanding tasks.
The first part of the presentation introduces the concept of integrating background and inference-time information, emphasizing that this is crucial for achieving comprehensive performance improvements on co-reference resolution datasets.
The second part focuses on the specific challenges faced by models when dealing with fictional entities during inference time. This section underscores the difficulty encountered by models trained without task-specific data, particularly highlighting their struggle to handle new entities introduced at test time due to the absence of pre-training parameters related to these entities.
The third part discusses the impact of task-specific training on model performance. The text explains how certain models successfully incorporate knowledge from different sources but still face difficulties when encountering unfamiliar entities or concepts not present in their initial training dataset.
The fourth part emphasizes the limitations of current models in handling such scenarios effectively. It mentions that while some models can generalize well under controlled conditions, they often fail to adapt to real-world situations where critical contextual clues are missing.
The fifth part provides an example scenario involving John's recent promotion as CEO, illustrating the complexities involved in accurately resolving references within sentences based on available context.
The sixth part elaborates further on the challenge posed by non-identifiable entities like "Chic" and "John," which complicate the process of entity identification and reference resolution in NLP systems.
The seventh part offers insights into the KITMUS test suite used to evaluate models’ abilities across various domains including finance, sports, movies, politics, technology, travel, business, law, education, science, healthcare, entertainment, music, fashion, food, games, retail, transportation, news, social media, and more.
The eighth part summarizes key takeaways about the importance of incorporating both pre-trained and inference-time knowledge for successful cross-referencing in NLP tasks.
The ninth part reiterates the need for domain-specific training to improve model performance significantly compared to random guessing strategies.
The tenth part concludes with recommendations for future work, suggesting enhancements through better incorporation of background knowledge and addressing issues raised earlier regarding model capabilities in integrating diverse types of information efficiently.
The eleventh part encourages viewers to explore the provided GitHub link (https://github.com/kitmus) for detailed evaluation results using the KITMUS dataset.

The slide shows the title "ABC-Eval" and includes a detailed bar graph comparing error rates for different models. The x-axis lists various evaluation metrics, such as "CS Contra," "Ignore," "Incorrect," etc., while the y-axis represents the percentage of turns. Different colored bars represent different model performances on these metrics.
The Emory University logo is visible in the bottom left corner, and an Amazon Alexa icon appears at the top right. A person's image is also present next to the Alexa icon throughout the presentation slides.
The content focuses on evaluating chatbot performance using ABC-Eval metrics across multiple conversational AI systems like BART-FID-RAG, Blender2, Emora, and Blender-Decode. It highlights how each system performs based on specific criteria related to conversational quality.
The slide transitions smoothly between sections, maintaining consistency with visual elements like logos and icons that reinforce the academic context of the research presented by Sarah Finch, James Finch, and Jinho Choi from Emory NLP Lab, supported by Professor G. C. H. Choi and Alexia.
Overall, it provides insights into comparative evaluations of chatbot effectiveness through concrete data visualization methods. <|speak|><|listen|>
